  <title>Different Bases</title>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>In the base-7 number system, the amount: 1 flat, 6 longs, and 5 small cubes is recorded as <m>165_{seven}</m> or <m>165_7</m>. In general, we record the base as a subscript except for base 10, since that is the assumed standard base.  Note that in base-7, 1 long is worth 7 small cubes, and 1 flat is worth 7 longs (which is 49 small cubes).</p>
      <p>For each number below, determine how many small cubes that number would consist of if we traded in all the base blocks for their corresponding number of small cubes.  In other words, what amount of small cubes is represented by each number in its corresponding base?</p>
      <ol type="a">
      <li><m>1202_{three}   = </m></li>
      <li><m>53_{seven}       = </m> </li>
      <li><m>203_{four}       = </m> </li>
      <li><m>10111_{two}       = </m> </li>
    </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>What are the place values after the decimal point in base 10? For example, write the expanded form of 1.29 to show the place values. What about the place values in base 5 after the decimal point (e.g., 12.345) ?</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

